parent_catalog_academic_advising_rosen_c.text:
The Rosen College Academic Support Team offers intentional targeted support services to help you reach your academic goals. In partnership with the Office of Student Success and Wellbeing, your Academic Success Coach, Internship Faculty Advisor and Student Services team will assist in guiding your progress throughout your educational journey.

Support for New Students

During Orientation, new Rosen College students will participate in group sessions led by the Academic Success Coaches to:

Review degree program policies and curriculum requirements;

Explore major career options and programs of study;

Learn about UCF’s Academic Coaching Model, key student success resources and the importance of the knights Email account for notifications;

Plan an appropriate first semester class schedule;

Navigate Pegasus Path and learn how to interpret the myKnight Audit, utilize advising resources tools through myUCF, and the Rosen College Undergraduate Webcourse.

Support for Continuing Students

Continuing student Knights should:

Utilize the "Rosen College Undergraduate Advising Guide" Webcourse as a resource to enhance degree completion;

See an Internship Faculty Advisor by Junior Year for assistance in interpreting and utilizing the experiential learning PREP modules;

View Pegasus Path for remaining degree requirements according to catalog year and course prerequisites prior to schedule planning and registration;

Schedule regular appointments with assigned Academic Success Coach to stay on track towards degree completion ;

After grades are posted each semester, view Degree Audit and Pegasus Path through myUCF to monitor progress and discuss any concerns with assigned Academic Success Coach or the college’s Office of Student Services ; and,

File an "Intent to Graduate" online through myUCF by the deadline published in the UCF Academic Calendar the semester prior to the term in which you plan to graduate.

parent_catalog_student_financial_assista.text:
To be considered for the full range of financial aid available, students should complete the Free Application for Federal Student Aid (FAFSA)/Renewal FAFSA by the established, published priority filing date. If the priority date is missed, students should apply as soon as possible after that date to be considered for the financial aid that is still available, such as the Federal Pell Grant, Federal Direct Stafford Loan, and Federal Direct PLUS Loan.

Students should not wait to be admitted to UCF before applying for financial aid; however, they cannot be offered a financial aid package until they have been admitted to the university;

Federal Pell Grants and Federal Direct Stafford Loans are available on a year-round basis. Students may apply for financial aid in advance of any term and receive aid from these programs, if eligible.

Students enrolling in the fall semester should submit all requested documents by the May 30th priority deadline for timely review and processing of their financial aid file. However, all students should have a completed financial aid file at least 60 days prior to the beginning of any given semester. Students who apply late for aid should be prepared to cover their own living expenses, out-of-pocket, well into the term;

A broad range of scholarships is available with diverse criteria. Please review the Scholarship page found on the website for additional information.

parent_catalog_undergraduate_admissions_.text:
Admission of Associate in Arts (A.A.) degree graduates from Florida College System institutions and Florida state universities is governed by the Articulation Agreement between the state universities and Florida College System institutions of Florida, as approved by the State Department of Education. The agreement states: The associate in arts degree is the basic transfer degree of the Florida College System institutions. It is the primary basis for admission of transfer students from Florida College System institutions to upper division study in a state university. Every associate in arts graduate of a Florida College System institution shall be granted admission to an upper division program consistent with Section 1007.23, F.S. Admission to each student's preferred public postsecondary institution or program is not guaranteed.

Any student admitted without demonstrated competency in a foreign language or American Sign Language equivalent to the second high school level or the elementary 2 level at an undergraduate institution must satisfy the admission requirement prior to graduation. Florida College System institution Associate in Arts graduates are guaranteed the following rights under the Statewide Articulation Agreement (State DOE Rule 6A-10.024):

Admission to one of the twelve state universities, except to "restricted access" programs (programs that have additional admission requirements);

Acceptance of at least 60 credit hours by the state universities toward the baccalaureate degree;

Transfer of equivalent courses under the statewide Course Numbering System;

Acceptance by the state universities of credit earned in accelerated programs (e.g., CLEP, AP, PEP, Dual Enrollment, Early Admission, and International Baccalaureate);

No additional General Education Core requirements;

Advanced knowledge of selection criteria for restricted access programs; and

Equal opportunity with native university students to enter limited programs.
